definition.value: An oxaspiro compound produced by Penicillium griseofulvum. It is used by mouth as an antifungal drug for infections involving the scalp, hair, nails and skin that do not respond to topical treatment.
A surfactant (or a mixture containing one or more surfactants) having cleaning properties in dilute solutions.
A tetradecenoic acid in which the double bond is at the 9-10 position and has Z configuration. Myristoleic acid has been isolated from Serenoa repens and has cytotoxic and apoptosis-inducing effects.
A ribonucleotide that is the 3'-dehydro derivative of adenosine 5'-triphosphate.
The methyl ester of amphotericin B.
A member of the class of chloroethanes substituted by two chloro groups at positions 1 and 2.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-tetraphosphate compound having 5'-uridinyl residues at the P(1)- and P(4)-positions.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of D- and L-cycloserine.
An epoxycarotenoid of beta-carotene.
A ferulic acid consisting of trans-cinnamic acid bearing methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 4 and 3 respectively on the phenyl ring.

An organic heterotetracyclic indole alkaloid isolated from the seeds and other parts of Erythrina species. It differs from the alpha isomer in having the double bond of the dihydropyranone ring located beta,gamma- to the lactone carbonyl group instead of alpha,beta-.
The amide obtained by formal condensation of 3,4,5-trihydroxybenzoic acid with 4-[2-(N,N-dimethylamino)ethoxy]benzylamine. It is used to prevent nausea and vomitting in humans.
A nitroarene consisting of benzene carrying a single nitro substituent. An industrial chemical used widely in the production of aniline.
A dihydroxybenzenesulfonic acid in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 2 and 3.
A 2-enoyl-CoA in which the double bond between positions 2 and 3 of the S-acyl group has cis- geometry.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of cyclohexanecarboxylic acid.

A morphinane alkaloid that is morphine bearing two acetyl substituents on the O-3 and O-6 positions. As with other opioids, heroin is used as both an analgesic and a recreational drug. Frequent and regular administration is associated with tolerance and physical dependence, which may develop into addiction. Its use includes treatment for acute pain, such as in severe physical trauma, myocardial infarction, post-surgical pain, and chronic pain, including end-stage cancer and other terminal illnesses.
A glutamic semialdehyde that is  L-glutamic 5-semialdehyde substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.
An aromatic ketone that is 1-phenylethanone substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4 and a methoxy group at position 3.
A  benzenediol that is benzene dihydroxylated at positions 1 and 3.
An undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl peptide in which the peptide moiety is L-alanyl-D-isoglutaminyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine.
An L-alpha-amino acid compound having methylselanylmethyl as the side-chain.
A long-chain fatty acid consisting of leukotriene B4 having a 12-keto group in place of the 12-hydroxy group.
A sialotetraosylceramide having alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-Gal-(1->3)-beta-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-Gal-(1->4)-beta-Glc as the sialotetraosyl component.
An organic heterobicyclic compound that is clavulanic acid in which the allylic alcohol group has been oxidised to the corresponding aldehyde.
A 2-methyl-3-oxopropanoic acid that has S-configuration.
A member of the class of benzimidazoles that is benzimidazole in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by an amino group.
A member of the class of indole-3-acetic acids that is  indole-3-acetic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at C-5.
A heteroarenecarbaldehyde that is thiamine(1+) in which the 2-hydroxyethyl group has been replaced by a 2-oxoethyl group.
A trimethoxyflavone that is  quercetin in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3, 4' and 7 have been replaced by methoxy groups.
A beta-D-glucoside consisting of (S)-prunasin carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
